node.text:
Understanding Natural Set Weight (aka Homeostatic Regulation of Body Fat Mass) ⚖️
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
You might’ve noticed my body changing a lot over the past 2 years and I commonly throw around the phrase “set weight” and “set point” so I want to give a deeper understanding as to what that means. My weight changed so much because when I truly listened to my hunger, my body needed time to adapt and find its genetically predetermined fat mass or set weight. This is more of a range, as it will fluctuate throughout my life. It also differs from person to person based on each person’s unique genetics and environment. 🧬🍽
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I tried to explain it to the best of my ability on these slides ➡️ but I also have an entire video on it on my YouTube channel called “The Science Behind My All In Journey” if you want a deeper dive 🎥

Which basically means it took less food for me to feel full during the meal (satiation) and had less interest in food after a meal (satiety). 10 years of trying to figure out health and fitness…AKA a very truncated version of my fitness journey.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I’ve been doing a lot of reflecting lately because I’ve been getting questions that make me wonder if people forget how old I am and how long it’s taken me to even begin “figuring things out” when it comes to my health… it’s been MANY years of trial and error 😅 (mostly error). So I figured I would show a very brief history of the last 10 years (I’m 31 if you didn’t know 🙃).
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
🗓 2011: Consistently weight training for ~1 year. I knew virtually nothing about dieting and nutrition.
🗓 2014: Weight training for ~3 years. Left: Starting point at the beginning of my first and only bikini prep. Right: Week of my bikini show.
🗓 2015: Holding onto some bizarre notion I needed to stay lean even though I was no longer competing. Diet was basically protein, rice, and veggies.
🗓 2016: Discovered flexible dieting. BUT was still lean and experiencing insatiable hunger from my previous bikini prep diet.
🗓 2017: Started my YouTube channel and felt pressured to look “good” so I kept my flexible dieting macros pretty low. (Funny how I didn’t think it was low at the time).
🗓 2018: Still haunted by my extreme hunger and decided to try a lean bulk to see if it would help. But I shortly gave up on bulking because I was starting to feel “fat” (ridiculous I know) and decided to do the complete opposite and ran a mini cut 🤦🏻‍♀️ 
🗓 Beginning of 2019: Ended my mini cut as shredded as I was when I competed. Miserable, tired and HUNGRY! All for what? Credibility? Notoriety? My ego? I’m not even sure 😞
🗓 Late 2019: All In and fixing my extreme hunger. Eating to complete satiety everyday.
🗓 2020: Hunger and satiety cues restored. Feeling healthy and happy but still working on listening to my body and intuitive eating.
🗓 2021: Strong, still happy and eating intuitively without restriction. Still a work in progress but getting there (wherever “there” is 😂🤔…self actualization? I dunno but I’m working on it)
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s been a long journey but hopefully I’ll continue to learn and grow. Nothing happens overnight…or a decade for that matter. Damn I’m old 😅

node.text:
How did I know All In was right for me?👇
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
You may already know all the obvious reasons like fixing my extreme hunger, correcting my hunger/satiety cues, increasing my metabolism, improving my strength and energy, not to mention all the health/hormonal benefits… but you may not know what exactly drove me over the edge to finally take the plunge.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It was simply because I tried EVERYTHING else to fix my hunger and nothing worked!
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
↩️ I tried reverse dieting, which left me even hungrier, frustrated and too focused on tracking my macros.
📈 I tried lean bulking, which didn’t do a damn thing to help my hunger and just caused some weight gain (which I felt the pressure to lose again on a mini cut because, ya know, the pressure to look fit).
🍽 I tried intuitive eating, which at that time I wasn’t ready for because all of my hunger and satiety signals were broken.
🍩 I tried the occasional cheat day which only gave me temporary relief from my hunger that would last 1 or 2 days, so obviously not a long term solution.
🕒 And I tried intermittent fasting so I would feel more satiated by eating all of my daily food in a smaller window of time. BUT I was still ravenous at the end of the feeding window, still never feeling satisfied.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I was miserable and desperate to find something that worked, and even though I wasn’t certain going All In was going to fix my problems…I was willing to try it. I was also sooo over trying to look a certain way for external validation that it was finally time to let that go. And I’m so happy I did ♥️
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
📸 Left: April 2019 | Right: October 2019 (5 months All In)

✨Confident✨
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I want to answer a question I get all the time and set the record straight. People always ask if “I am happy or feel more confident because I’ve lost some of my overshoot weight?” I’ve answered this on YT but I just want to address it again. Short answer: Absolutely not.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Long answer: I had no clue whatsoever what weight I would end up. I had a rough idea of what my natural set weight was but it changes throughout your life, so there was no way to predict exactly what would happen after I went All In. Despite that, I’ve been significantly happier and more confident for a long time (well before I lost any of the overshoot weight I initially gained). I haven’t done anything intentionally to induce weight loss and to the contrary, I’ve been actively trying to increase my appetite out of fear of decreasing my metabolism due to my lack of appetite.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I did what I had to do two years ago because I desperately wanted to fix my extreme hunger. I WAS DESPERATE. I would’ve done ANYTHING. I was so miserable, in a state of being perpetually hangry and the reason I am so happy is because I fixed it! 😭 I no longer feel insatiable hunger, I no longer feel weak, tired or moody. I haven’t felt that in over a year and it is the most glorious feeling in the world. If you’ve ever experienced extreme hunger, you will understand where I’m coming from. I feel free, that is why I am happy. Period.🕊

Just doing my intuitive eating thing, eating the meals that I enjoy and make me feel satisfied. As a self proclaimed foodie, I love trying new and fun foods but on a day-to-day basis, I essentially eat very similar meals. It makes my groceries and planning my meals much easier 😋

 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Lunch 🥪🥑🥔

-Multi-grain bread

Berries & Kiwi

As bashful as I am about the prospect, I wanted to officially announce that I signed with a publisher for my book! 🙏🎉📖
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
This book will be something I wish I had when I embarked on my own All In journey. I wished I had a resource or a friend that had done it before me so I could have someone to relate to and have someone who understands how difficult it is. I want to create a source of comfort and to share what I went through so it can be a resource for those who need it. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I would like readers to learn through my experience that there is another way to live beyond a life of always being hungry, tired and weak from dieting and food restriction. That there is a way to live without fear foods and the constant fear of gaining weight. I want women and men to love their body at whatever body weight, as long as their body is healthy, strong and energized. Living within the confines of societal pressure just to look a certain way only drains people of their natural hunger and satiety cues and condemns them to a life of a never-ending weight loss and weight gain cycle. Hopefully my experience will show them that it is possible because I did it ♥️
